Developers, Galaxy Entertainment: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   N i c k   G e n t l e
-- 
2011-05-05T01:10:26Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-05/developers-galaxy-entertainment-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  fell 1.4 percent to 23,315.24. The Hang
Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, slid 1.8 percent to 12,866.59.  Developers: Hong Kong home sales fell to the lowest volume
in more than two years in April as government curbs and rising
mortgage rates sapped demand after a price surge since 2009. The
number of units that changed hands last month declined 37.6
percent from a year earlier to 7,635, according to a statement
on the Land Registry website yesterday.  Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd. (16)  (16 HK): The world’s largest-
listed developer, fell 0.7 percent to HK$120.30.  Cheung Kong
Holdings Ltd. (1)  (1 HK), controlled by billionaire  Li Ka-shing ,
dropped 0.9 percent to HK$119.60. Henderson Land Development Co.
(12 HK), which receives 84 percent of revenue in the city,
declined 2.9 percent to HK$51.25.  China Petroleum & Chemical Corp. (386)  (386 HK): The refiner and
oil seller plans to build a 2.6 million metric-ton-a-year diesel
hydrotreater at its Yanshan oil refinery, parent China
Petrochemical Corp. said in its on-line newsletter today. The
plan has been submitted to the government for approval.
Construction of new unit at the refinery will begin this year
and may be completed as early as 2012, China Petrochemical said.
The stock fell 1.8 percent to HK$7.57.  Galaxy Entertainment Group Ltd. (27)  (27 HK): The casino
operator has bought all advertising space in Hong Kong’s Tsim
Sha Tsui subway station, almost 10,000 square meters, until the
end of the month to promote the opening of the Galaxy Macau
resort, the  South China Morning Post  said, citing Amy Chan,
managing director of JCDecaux Transport Hong Kong, the city
subway operator’s station-advertising agent. Galaxy Macau
declined to give the cost of the campaign, the Hong Kong-based
English-language newspaper reported today. The stock fell 3.4
percent to HK$13.72.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Nick Gentle at   ngentle2@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at   ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 